page.text: In 2008, the Fargo Moorhead Metropolitan Council of Governments (FMM COG) prepared a Corridor Study

roadway improvement needs along US 75 (also known as 8th Street South) from 20th Avenue South to 60th
Avenue South, including its interchange with I-94. These improvements were based on conditions in 2006,
as well as projected year 2035 traffic volumes based on land development patterns in the area.
Based on traffic operations analysis for current and future conditions, the study recommended widening
US 75 to a six-lane roadway with turn lanes from 20th Avenue South to 40th Avenue South, and the addition
of loops for the eastbound-to-northbound exit movement, and the northbound-to-westbound entrance
As part of MnDOT project number S.P. 1406-66, this ICE report will examine intersection control alternatives
under pre-design activities for the I-94 and US 75 ramp intersections.

Capacity analysis results identify a level of service (LOS), which indicates how well an intersection is
operating. The LOS results at an intersection are based on average delay per vehicle. The LOS system rates
the intersection using the letters A through F, with LOS A being least congested and LOS F being most
congested. At LOS C, roads remain safely below but efficiently close to capacity, and posted speed is often
maintained. LOS D is a common design goal for urban streets during peak hours. While LOS E is a common
design goal in larger urban areas, where some roadway congestion is inevitable, the threshold for acceptable
traffic operations used in this analysis was LOS D. A summary of the LOS thresholds from the Highway
Capacity Manual is shown in Table 3.1.

The Roundabout Alternative assumes that the existing diamond interchange configuration with roundabouts at
the north and south ramps. The intersections of 24th Avenue and 30th Avenue will remain signalized. Figure
7 shows the conceptual layout for the Roundabout Alternative and Figure 8 shows the year 2035 LOS results
by traffic movement. Results of the VISSIM analysis for the year 2035 Roundabout Alternative indicate that
24th and 30th Avenue intersections will likely operate at an unacceptable LOS E or F during the a.m. peak
hour, and the 24th Avenue intersection will continue to operate at an unacceptable LOS E during the p.m.
peak under year 2035 build conditions. While the proposed roundabouts may operate at acceptable overall
LOS during the a.m. and p.m. peak hours under year 2035 build traffic conditions, Figure 8 shows that
westbound and southbound approaches at the I-94 North Ramp intersection will operate at unacceptable LOS
E or F during the a.m. and p.m. peak hours and the eastbound approach at the I-94 South Ramp intersection
will operate at an unacceptable LOS E during the p.m. peak hour.
Therefore, roundabouts are not a viable alternative for the I-94/US 75 interchange ramps intersections
because of poor traffic operations under year 2035 build traffic conditions.

top of the ramps as the north- and southbound traffic work into one lane of flow. However, the congestion
does clear regularly during the peak hours and does not cause significant disruption to other traffic in the
Therefore, the analysis shows that a DDI interchange would provide better traffic operations when compared

DIVERGING DIAMOND INTERCHANGE (DDI) ALTERNATIVE WITH INDI RECT LEFT-TUR NS
This scenario examines the intersection under year 2035 traffic volumes and DDI under signalized control,
and indirect left-turns at the 30th Avenue intersection. Figure 11 shows the conceptual layout for a DDI
under year 2035 build conditions and Figure 12 shows the year 2035 LOS results by traffic movement.
Results of the VISSIM analysis for the year 2035 DDI alternative with indirect left-turns at 30th Avenue
indicate that all four of the key intersections will continue operate at acceptable LOS D or better during the
a.m. and p.m. peak hours (similar to the DDI Alternative). However, as shown in Figure 12, more individual
traffic movements will report unacceptable LOS during the a.m. and p.m. peak hours under the DDI alternative
with indirect left-turns; particularly at the 24th Avenue and 30th Avenue intersections.
The primary benefit of the proposed indirect left-turns at 30th Avenue is the decrease in the likelihood that
southbound traffic will back up from the 30th Avenue intersection to the I-94 South Ramps. This backup is
currently reported under existing conditions. However, under future build conditions US 75 will need to be
upgraded to three lanes in each direction. The additional lane in each direction will provide more roadway
capacity and additional storage for southbound US 75 between 30th Avenue and the I-94 interchange,
ultimately reducing the likelihood of southbound traffic backing up to the I-94 South Ramps.
Therefore, the analysis shows that while the DDI interchange alternative with indirect left-turns at 30th
Avenue will would provide better traffic operations when compared with the existing signalized diamond
interchange; the indirect left-turns at 30th Avenue will likely result in reduced levels of service for eastbound
and westbound traffic movements at 30th Avenue during the a.m. and p.m. peak hours.

page.text: This alternative was an initial concept from the Value Engineering (VE) Study. The NE Loop alternative is a
standard diamond interchange with one loop in the northeast quadrant for northbound to westbound traffic.
This scenario examines the intersections under year 2035 traffic volumes and a NE Loop interchange under
signalized control. Figure 13 shows the conceptual layout for a NE Loop interchange under year 2035 build
conditions and Figure 14 shows the year 2035 LOS results by traffic movement.
Results of the VISSIM analysis for the year 2035 NE Loop alternative indicate that all four of the key
intersections will operate at acceptable LOS D or better during the a.m. and p.m. peak hours. As shown in
Figure 14, the 24th Avenue and 30th Avenue intersections will report the majority of the individual traffic
movements at LOS E or F, and again this will primarily occur on the eastbound and westbound approaches on
24th and 30th Avenues during the a.m. and p.m. peak hours.
The westbound I-94 on-ramp from US 75 in the NE Loop alternative is only used by southbound US 75 traffic.
This is the advantage of the NE loop – it places northbound and southbound US 75 traffic on to I-94 at two
separate locations. The westbound I-94 on-ramp must merge to one lane of traffic before the bottom of the
ramp alongside the two I-94 through lanes. This ramp from US 75 enters I-94 into a separate third through
lane. The VISSIM simulation shows minor congestion as the southbound traffic works into one lane of flow.
Once the westbound I-94 on-ramp traffic works in to one lane, it will merge into the northbound to
westbound traffic that has entered the freeway into a new third lane from the proposed loop in the northeast
quadrant of the interchange. There appears to be just enough space to include a standard acceleration lane
from the ramp onto I-94 before the bridge. It should be noted that under this alternative, a third lane will be
needed on I-94 from the proposed NE loop to the Red River Bridge. The third lane exists from the current
westbound ramp, but will need to be extended to the proposed loop.
The analysis shows that a NE Loop interchange would provide better traffic operations when compared with
the existing signalized diamond interchange. The NE Loop interchange will also likely improve the
traffic operations at the I-94 North Ramp intersection during the p.m. peak hour, when compared to
the DDI Interchange alternatives. However, the I-94 South Ramp intersection will not operate as well
under the NE Loop Alternative as it does under the DDI Alternative.

This scenario examines the intersection under year 2035 traffic volumes and a NE Loop interchange under
signalized control, and indirect left-turns at the 30th Avenue intersection. Figure 15 shows the conceptual
layout for a NE Loop interchange with indirect left-turns at 30th Avenue under year 2035 build conditions and
Figure 16 shows the year 2035 LOS results by traffic movement.
Results of the VISSIM analysis for the year 2035 DDI alternative with indirect left-turns at 30th Avenue
indicate that all four of the key intersections will continue operate at acceptable LOS D or better during the
a.m. and p.m. peak hours (similar to the NE Loop alternative). The addition of the indirect left at 30th Avenue
helps the interchange marginally. There is a reduced risk of southbound traffic backing up from 30th to the
interchange with the indirect left-turn at 30th Avenue. However, as shown in Figure 16, more individual
traffic movements will report unacceptable LOS under the NE Loop alternative with indirect left-turns;
particularly at the 24th Avenue and 30th Avenue intersections during the p.m. peak hour.
Therefore, the analysis shows that while the NE Loop interchange alternative with indirect left-turns at 30th
Avenue will would provide better traffic operations when compared with the existing signalized diamond
interchange and helps to reduce the likelihood of southbound traffic backing up from 30th Avenue to
the interchange; the indirect left-turns at 30th Avenue will likely result in reduced levels of service for
eastbound and westbound traffic movements at the 24th and 30th Avenue intersections during the p.m. peak
hours when compared to the NE Loop alternative without the indirect left-turns at 30th Avenue.

page.text: This alternative was one of the alternatives recommended for consideration through the VE Study. The ParClo
alternative is a standard partial cloverleaf concept. In this case the northbound to westbound and
southbound to eastbound movements are facilitated by loops in the northeast and southwest quadrants of
the interchange. The original ParClo interchange layout did not include the ramp to eastbound I-94 in the
southeast quadrant. As a result, all traffic to eastbound I-94 was directed through the loop in the southwest
quadrant. Since the VE Study Committee did not intend that the eastbound I-94 ramp be eliminated from the
ParClo alternative, and further review indicated that the ramp is needed in order to accommodate the heavy
northbound to eastbound traffic movement at the I-94 South Ramp intersection, the free right to the
eastbound I-94 ramp in the southeast quadrant was added back to the layout.
This scenario examines the intersections under year 2035 traffic volumes and a ParClo interchange under
signalized control. Figure 17 shows the conceptual layout for a ParClo interchange under year 2035 build
conditions and Figure 18 shows the year 2035 LOS results by traffic movement.

intersections will operate at acceptable LOS D or better during the a.m. and p.m. peak hours. As shown in
Figure 18, the 24th Avenue intersection will report the majority of the individual traffic movements at LOS E
or F, and again this will primarily occur on the eastbound and westbound 24th Avenue approaches during the
Similar to the NE Loop alternative, the westbound I-94 on-ramp from US 75 in the ParClo alternative is only
used by southbound US 75 traffic. This is the advantage of the NE loop – it places the US 75 traffic on to I-
94 in two separate locations. The ramp must merge to one lane of traffic before the bottom of the ramp
alongside the two I-94 through lanes. This ramp from US 75 enters I-94 into a separate third through lane.
There is minor congestion as the southbound traffic works into one lane of flow. Once the westbound on-
ramp traffic works in to one lane, it will merge into the northbound to westbound traffic that has entered the
freeway into a new third lane from the loop in the northeast quadrant. There appears to be just enough
space to include a standard acceleration lane from the ramp onto I-94 before the bridge.
The analysis shows that a ParClo interchange would provide better traffic operations when compared with
the existing signalized diamond interchange. Similar to the NE Loop interchange alternative, the ParClo
interchange will also likely improve the traffic operations at the I-94 North Ramp intersection during the
p.m. peak hour, when compared to the DDI interchange alternatives. However, the I-94 South Ramp
intersection will not operate as well under the ParClo alternative as it does under the DDI alternative.

Due to increasing traffic volumes projected by 2035, it is recommended that a DDI is constructed at the
